The parallel development is documented in the Keepers of Measure's Littoral Branch records — coastal survey tradition developed ceramic-tablet documentation for maritime contexts at roughly the same time as the inland Scorching Sands tradition, both descending from the same Measure Script notation system.
Mafdet's Ledger Houses and the Water Court have reciprocal recognition of each other's ceramic-tablet records: a kiln-sealed tablet from either system is accepted as primary evidence in both.
The reciprocal recognition predates any five-city formal agreement and represents the most direct surviving institutional connection between the inland Keeper-era legal tradition and the maritime Keepers of Measure's Littoral Branch tradition.

